# Strong types

Prefer strong types over raw primitives. System boundaries (user input, file
reads, environment variables) are the exception — coerce to strong types as
early as possible after crossing the boundary.

## Pathname for file/directory paths

Use `Pathname`, not `String`. Coerce in constructors with `Pathname()`.

```ruby
# BAD
def initialize(dir:)
  @dir = dir  # could be String or Pathname
end

# GOOD
def initialize(dir:)
  @dir = Pathname(dir)
end
```

Use Pathname's `/` operator for path joins instead of `File.join`:

```ruby
# BAD
path = File.join(@dir.to_s, "deps.lock")

# GOOD
path = @dir / "deps.lock"
```

Constants holding filenames get a `_FILE` suffix:

```ruby
# BAD
DEPS_LOCK = "deps.lock"
DEPS_CMAKE = "deps.cmake"

# GOOD
DEPS_LOCK_FILE = "deps.lock"
DEPS_CMAKE_FILE = "deps.cmake"
```

## URI for URLs

Coerce URL strings to `URI` in constructors. Downstream code works with
the `URI` object and calls `.to_s` only at system boundaries (e.g.,
passing to `system("brew", "tap", ...)`).

```ruby
# BAD
Tap = Data.define(:name, :url)  # url is a raw String

# GOOD
Tap = Data.define(:name, :url) do
  def initialize(name:, url: nil)
    super(name:, url: url ? URI(url).freeze : nil)
  end
end
```

## Domain objects at parsing boundaries

Build domain value objects at the system boundary (parser, DSL builder,
config loader) rather than passing raw hashes or arrays through layers.

```ruby
# BAD: parser returns raw hash, consumer builds domain object later
def parse(path)
  { name: yaml["name"], version: yaml["version"] }
end

# GOOD: parser returns domain object immediately
def parse(path)
  DependencyDeclaration.new(name: yaml["name"], version: yaml["version"])
end
```

## Never use `T.untyped` in Sorbet signatures

Every Sorbet-typed field and parameter must use a concrete type. If you
reach for `T.untyped`, that is a design signal — restructure so the
type can be stated explicitly.

```ruby
# BAD
const :command_runner, T.untyped

# GOOD
const :ui, Dev::Cli::Ui
const :ruby_version, String
const :project_root, Pathname
```
